<p><ent>Frank</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Frank
<hw>Frank</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To shut up in a frank or sty; to
pen up; hence, to cram; to fatten.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frank</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Frank
<hw>Frank</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The common heron;
-- so called from its note.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 593 --></p>

<p><ent>frank</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: frank
<hw>frank</hw> <pr>(fr⟦acr⟧⟦nsm⟧k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>franker</adjf>
<pr>(fr⟦acr⟧⟦nsm⟧k"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>frankest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[F. <ets>franc</ets> free, frank,
L. <ets>Francus</ets> a Frank, fr. OHG. <ets>Franko</ets> the name of a
Germanic people on the Rhine, who afterward founded the French monarchy;
cf. AS. <ets>franca</ets> javelin, Icel. <ets>frakka</ets>. Cf.
<er>Franc</er>, <er>French</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, <er>Franchise</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Unbounded by restrictions,
limitations, etc.; free.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧It is of
<xex>frank</xex> gift.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Free in uttering one's real sentiments; not
reserved; using no disguise; candid; ingenuous; <as>as, a <ex>frank</ex>
nature, conversation, manner, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Liberal; generous; profuse.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Frank</qex> of civilities that cost them nothing.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Unrestrained; loose; licentious; -- used in a bad
sense.</def> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Ingenuous; candid; artless; plain; open;
unreserved; undisguised; sincere. See <er>Candid</er>,
<er>Ingenuous</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>frank</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: frank
<hw>frank</hw> <pr>(fr⟦acr⟧⟦nsm⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>franked</conjf>
<pr>(fr⟦acr⟧⟦nsm⟧kt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>franking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To send by public
conveyance free of expense.</def> <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To extempt from charge for postage, as a letter,
package, or packet, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frank</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Frank
<hw>Frank</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Frank</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>The privilege of sending letters or other mail
matter, free of postage, or without charge; also, the sign, mark, or
signature denoting that a letter or other mail matter is to go free of
postage. Called also the <altname><ecol><b>franking
privilege</b></ecol></altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have said so much, that, if I had not a <qex>frank</qex>, I must
burn my letter and begin again.</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frank</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Frank
<hw>Frank</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>franc</ets>. See
<er>Frank</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld>
<def>A member of one of the German tribes that in the fifth century
overran and conquered Gaul, and established the kingdom of
France.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A native or inhabitant of Western Europe; a
European; -- a term used in the Levant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A French coin. See <er>Franc</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frankalmoigne</ent>⟦br⟧
